0% on hotels (around ฿700–1,500 a night) and enjoy quiet beaches. Only beach-only, inflexible trips should think twice."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How bad is the rain in Pattaya during the wet season?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Less bad than its reputation. A typical day is bright in the morning, then a heavy 30–90 minute thunderstorm in the afternoon, clearing to a fresh evening. September and October are the wettest, when you may get the odd grey day and brief street flooding, but all-day rain is the exception, not the rule."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "When is Pattaya's rainy season?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Roughly May to October. May and June are the driest part with short storms and good beach hours, July and August are reliably wet but follow the afternoon-burst pattern, and September and October are the wettest weeks. By late October the rain eases as the cool season approaches."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can you still swim and go to Koh Larn in the rainy season?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Usually, yes. The sea stays warm at around 29–30°C and you can swim on most days, though water can get murkier and choppier after storms. Koh Larn ferries from Bali Hai pier (฿30 each way) generally run all season, but on genuinely rough days, especially in September–October, services thin out or stop."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How much cheaper is Pattaya in the rainy season?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Significantly cheaper on accommodation. Mid-range rooms that cost ฿1,400–2,800 in December–February drop to about ฿700–1,500 in the wet months, and beachfront rooms in Pratumnak or Wong Amat become affordable. Food (฿50–120 street meals) and transport (฿10–30 songthaews) stay cheap year-round, so a mid-range day runs around ฿1,400–2,400."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What should you pack for Pattaya in the rainy season?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Pack light and practical: a cheap ฿50–100 poncho from any 7-Eleven, quick-dry sandals you don't mind getting wet, and a dry bag for your phone. A flexible hotel booking and travel insurance that covers weather disruption are the two smart add-ons. You won't need heavy waterproofs — the storms are warm and brief."}}]}]$b$);
